  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The Pawtucket Juvenile Anti-Slavery Society has requested that Elizabeth B. Chace ask Maria Weston Chapman to contribute an article to a little book to be issued for sale at their annual fair and to be called &quot;The Slaves Memorial&quot; or the like. Chace asks Maria W. Chapman to ask Edmund Quincy, Lydia Maria Child, and others to write for it. Chace concludes the letter by exclaiming: &quot;Oh! how deceived you have been in Dr. Manford.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Dr. Manford is an alias for John Colman. See William Lloyd Garrison, Vol. II, note 348; &quot;His titular name [Dr. Manford] like his anti-slavery profession, was put on.&quot; For another reference to Dr. Manford, see the letter dated July 9, 1840, by Edmund Quincy to Caroline Weston, Call No. Ms.A.9.2 v.13, p.99.</subfield>
  </datafield>
